{"count": 28681, "next": "https://api.acmi.net.au/creators/?page=1485", "previous": "https://api.acmi.net.au/creators/?page=1483", "results": [{"id": 34476, "name": "Jorge Fons", "roles_in_work": [{"id": 1996610, "title": "Midaq Alley = El Callejon de los Milagros", "work_id": 92774, "role": "director", "role_id": 938, "is_primary": true}], "also_known_as": "", "date_of_birth": "1939-04-23", "date_of_death": "2022-09-22", "genders": [{"id": 9, "name": "Male", "slug": "male"}], "languages": [{"id": 10, "name": "Spanish", "slug": "spanish"}], "places_of_operation": [{"id": 185, "name": "Mexico", "slug": "mexico"}], "biography": "Jorge Fons Pérez (born in Tuxpan, Veracruz, Mexico on 23 April 1939) is a Mexican film director.\nHe belongs to the first generation of film directors of the UNAM. His short film, Caridad (1973), is still considered one of the best films in Mexican cinema. Two of the most important films of his filmography are Rojo amanecer (1989) and El callejón de los milagros (1995) based in the homonym book by Naguib Mahfouz, Midaq Alley  of 1947 (زقاق المدق), which breaks the classic lineal plots in films.\nHis 1976 film, Los albañiles, won the Silver Bear at the 27th Berlin International Film Festival. In 1995, his film El callejón de los milagros won a Special Mention at the 45th Berlin International Film Festival.", "biography_author": "Wikidata", "date_of_biography": "2022-05-19T12:04:57.766980+10:00", "external_links": [{"id": 2460, "uri": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jorge_Fons"}], "uuid": "1768feea-07f6-449b-b0f7-49b33b089ecd", "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "22690", "external_references": [{"id": 10517, "source": {"name": "Wikidata", "slug": "wikidata"}, "source_identifier": "Q612737"}, {"id": 10518, "source": {"name": "VIAF", "slug": "viaf"}, "source_identifier": "4478952"}, {"id": 10519, "source": {"name": "LOC Auth", "slug": "loc-auth"}, "source_identifier": "no00072266"}, {"id": 10520, "source": {"name": "WorldCat", "slug": "worldcat"}, "source_identifier": "lccn-no00072266"}], "date_modified": "2023-09-13T12:30:39.652311+10:00"}, {"id": 34475, "name": "Alfredo Ripstein Jr", "roles_in_work": [{"id": 1996609, "title": "Midaq Alley = El Callejon de los Milagros", "work_id": 92774, "role": "producer", "role_id": 1089, "is_primary": true}], "also_known_as": "", "date_of_birth": "1916-12-10", "date_of_death": "2007-01-20", "genders": [{"id": 9, "name": "Male", "slug": "male"}], "languages": [{"id": 10, "name": "Spanish", "slug": "spanish"}], "places_of_operation": [{"id": 185, "name": "Mexico", "slug": "mexico"}], "biography": "Alfredo Ripstein (Alfredo Ripstein Aronovich) (December 10, 1916, Parral, Chihuahua, Mexico — January 20, 2007, Mexico City) was a Mexican film producer of European-Jewish descent. He is credited with helping shape Mexico's film industry in the period surrounding World War II.Ripstein also helped start the careers of several contemporary Mexican actors such as Gael García Bernal and Salma Hayek.\n\n", "biography_author": "Wikidata", "date_of_biography": "2022-05-19T10:46:16.582937+10:00", "external_links": [{"id": 1612, "uri": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfredo_Ripstein"}], "uuid": "b49d1cbf-c355-4774-a9bb-8777d8cb159c", "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "14966", "external_references": [{"id": 7050, "source": {"name": "Wikidata", "slug": "wikidata"}, "source_identifier": "Q2153025"}, {"id": 7051, "source": {"name": "VIAF", "slug": "viaf"}, "source_identifier": "181149066358165600721"}, {"id": 7052, "source": {"name": "LOC Auth", "slug": "loc-auth"}, "source_identifier": "no2003009972"}, {"id": 7053, "source": {"name": "WorldCat", "slug": "worldcat"}, "source_identifier": "lccn-no2003009972"}], "date_modified": "2023-09-13T12:28:07.862774+10:00"}, {"id": 34469, "name": "Skyline Films", "roles_in_work": [{"id": 2288892, "title": "The Trench", "work_id": 92771, "role": "production company", "role_id": 941, "is_